// Q.  What is an Array?
// A.  let arr = [1, 2, 3];
//     But internally:
//     👉 JS arrays are dynamic, resizable, ordered objects
//     👉 Indexed with 0-based indexing
//     👉 Not fixed-size like C++

//     Under the hood:
//     🔹V8 (JS engine) optimizes arrays as contiguous memory (like C++) until you break it.
//     🔹If you insert weird stuff → becomes hash map-like structure.
    
//     Example:
//     let arr = [1, 2, 3];
//     arr[100] = 5; // sparse array
//     // V8 internally treats it like:
//     {
//       0: 1,
//       1: 2,
//       2: 3,
//       100: 5
//       // indices 3–99 don't exist at all in memory
//     }
//     console.log(arr.length);      // 101
//     console.log(arr[3]);          // undefined (not stored)
//     console.log(3 in arr);        // false ✅ (key doesn't exist)
//     console.log(100 in arr);      // true  ✅ (key exists)
//     console.log(0 in arr);        // true  ✅
//     V8 doesn't waste memory filling 3–99 with undefined. It just switches the array to a dictionary/hash-map structure and only stores real values. The "holes" are just the absence of key

