// Some Array Travesing-Techniques:
// 1.  Two Pointers-
//     Use two indices to traverse an array (or string, or linked list) simultaneously. Instead of an O(n²) nested loop that checks every pair, two pointers reduce the work to a single O(n) pass — each element is visited at most once.
//     The trick: the data must have a monotone property (usually sortedness) so you know which pointer to advance at each step.

//     The 3 strategies -
//     ↔ Opposite ends
//     Left starts at index 0, right at n−1. They march inward. Move left when you need a bigger value, right when you need smaller.
//     Use when: find a pair/triplet, reverse in-place, water container.
//     Ex- left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
//     167. Two Sum II - Input Array Is Sorted

//     →→ Slow / fast
//     Both start at the beginning. Fast advances ahead of slow. The gap between them captures something useful.
//     Use when: find middle of list, detect cycle, remove duplicates, sliding window.
//     Ex- slow = 0, fast = 0; while (fast < arr.length) { if (arr[slow] !== arr[fast]) { slow++; arr[slow] = arr[fast]; } fast++; }
//     876. Middle of the Linked List

//     ⇒⇒ Independent
//     One pointer per sequence. Always advance the pointer at the smaller element.
//     Use when: merge two sorted arrays, intersection of two lists.
//     Ex- i = 0, j = 0; while (i < arr1.length && j < arr2.length) { ... };
//     88. Merge Sorted Array